[
    [
        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "4.2 Teleportation (Bennet et al. 1993)"
                    }
                ],
                "level": 2
            },
            "bbox": [
                139,
                123,
                618,
                144
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "The teleportation protocol allows Alice to “send” an unknown qubit <sub>|</sub> <sub>i</sub> to Bob without using a quantum channel, i.e. without physically sending the qubit, but using only a classical channel, as for example a phone communication. To achieve this, Alice and Bob share a pair of qubits in the entangled state "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "\\begin{array} { r } { | \\beta _ { 0 0 } \\rangle = \\frac { | 0 0 \\rangle + | 1 1 \\rangle } { \\sqrt { 2 } } } \\end{array}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ". Alice entangles her qubit with the unknown qubit "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "| \\psi \\rangle = \\alpha | 0 \\rangle + \\beta | 1 \\rangle"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "she wants to teleport, using a CNOT gate. She then applies the Hadamard gate to the first qubit (the qubit that originally was in the state <sub>|</sub> <sub>i</sub>) and measures the two qubits. After this, Alice telephones the result of her meaurements to Bob. According to the result 00, 01, 10, 11 communicated by Alice, Bob e↵ects one of four operations on his qubit , respectively "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "I , Z , X , Z X"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ", and by so doing transforms the state of his qubit exactly in the state <sub>|</sub> <sub>i</sub> of the qubit originally owned by Alice."
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                137,
                152,
                860,
                344
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "The corresponding quantum circuit is"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                169,
                356,
                500,
                372
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": {
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/e9a97c59f601119511ce6d6eeeb77a0e73ee7b5c65e4b26b28cadd0243fd1e6c.jpg"
                },
                "content": "```mermaid\ngraph LR\n  t3 -->|X_Z[\"X\\nZ\"]| t3\n  t3 -->|X_Z| t3\n  t3 -->|X_Z| t3\n  t3 -->|X_Z| t3\n```",
                "image_caption": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Fig. 4.1 Teleportation circuit"
                    }
                ],
                "image_footnote": []
            },
            "sub_type": "flowchart",
            "bbox": [
                186,
                406,
                823,
                514
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "a 3-qubit circuit where the upper two qubits belong to Alice and the lower qubit belongs to Bob. By following the evolution of the initial 3-qubit state "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "( \\alpha | 0 \\rangle +"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "\\beta | 1 \\rangle ) \\frac { | \\bar { 0 } 0 \\rangle + | 1 1 \\rangle } { \\sqrt { 2 } }"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "across the CNOT and H gates, one finds that the 3-qubit state before Alice measurements is"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                137,
                560,
                858,
                630
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "equation_interline",
            "content": {
                "math_content": "\\frac {1}{2} \\left[ | 0 0 \\rangle (\\alpha | 0 \\rangle + \\beta | 1 \\rangle) + | 0 1 \\rangle (\\alpha | 1 \\rangle + \\beta | 0 \\rangle) + | 1 0 \\rangle (\\alpha | 0 \\rangle - \\beta | 1 \\rangle) + | 1 1 \\rangle (\\alpha | 1 \\rangle - \\beta | 0 \\rangle) \\right] \\tag {4.1}",
                "math_type": "latex",
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/d77501d6f83fff25aa485af6547ddd8bbb6603c6a2a1b5a43461bef2cd128759.jpg"
                }
            },
            "bbox": [
                156,
                638,
                853,
                686
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "A measurement by Alice produces a collapse into one of the four states contained in this superposition. For example if Alice measures 01 the state (4.1) collapses into"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                137,
                686,
                857,
                722
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "equation_interline",
            "content": {
                "math_content": "\\left| 0 1 \\right\\rangle (\\alpha | 1 \\rangle + \\beta | 0 \\rangle) \\tag {4.2}",
                "math_type": "latex",
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/cef7ec08f74fc2050f134f7db9f0d7f3d5e9a7e4116d31b7a7499ea4f8815cd1.jpg"
                }
            },
            "bbox": [
                423,
                733,
                853,
                752
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "This state is a product state, with Bob’s qubit in the state"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                139,
                766,
                653,
                783
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "equation_interline",
            "content": {
                "math_content": "\\alpha | 1 \\rangle + \\beta | 0 \\rangle \\tag {4.3}",
                "math_type": "latex",
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/35872c5b2010b08cd559616c032a71b64347d054a2380951555aa36fc493d4d3.jpg"
                }
            },
            "bbox": [
                445,
                796,
                853,
                815
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Alice phones her result 01 to Bob, so that Bob learns that his qubit is in the state (4.3). He therefore applies to it the gate X and reconstructs the original "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "| \\psi \\rangle = \\alpha | 0 \\rangle + \\beta | 1 \\rangle"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "state."
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                137,
                828,
                858,
                881
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "page_number",
            "content": {
                "page_number_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "20"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                485,
                906,
                510,
                919
            ]
        }
    ],
    [
        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "<sub>•</sub> Observations:"
                    }
                ],
                "level": 2
            },
            "bbox": [
                139,
                125,
                295,
                142
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "list",
            "content": {
                "list_type": "text_list",
                "list_items": [
                    {
                        "item_type": "text",
                        "item_content": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "content": "i) the state <sub>|</sub> <sub>i</sub> is teleported at a speed always "
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "equation_inline",
                                "content": "\\leq c ."
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "content": ", since it is limited by the speed of the classical communication."
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "item_type": "text",
                        "item_content": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "content": "ii) the original state <sub>|</sub> <sub>i</sub> owned by Alice gets destroyed (by measurement), so that there is no violation of the no cloning theorem."
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "item_type": "text",
                        "item_content": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "content": "iii) teleportation is not vulnerable to noise, since it does not use a physical carrier. (The classical part of the protocol, i.e. communication of Alice’ results to Bob, could be disturbed by classical causes)."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                137,
                156,
                855,
                304
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "5 Lecture 5"
                    }
                ],
                "level": 2
            },
            "bbox": [
                139,
                328,
                329,
                349
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "5.1 Quantum parallelism"
                    }
                ],
                "level": 2
            },
            "bbox": [
                139,
                366,
                457,
                385
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Quantum gates implement linear operations, and therefore can operate in parallel on all the states contained in a superposition. Consider a Boolean function f , i.e. a function taking N bits into 1 bit. Thus the domain of f is the set of binary N-bit integers x and the image is <sub>{</sub>0, 1<sub>}</sub>. By <sub>|</sub>x<sub>i</sub> we denote the N-qubit state specified by the string of 0’s and 1’s in x: thus for "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "\\mathrm { N } { = } 4"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "if "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "x = 0 1 1 0"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ", then "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "| x \\rangle = | 0 \\rangle | 1 \\rangle | 1 \\rangle | 0 \\rangle"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ". We define now a unitary "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "\\mathrm { N } { + } 1"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "qubit operator "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "U _ { f }"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "that acts on the computational basis of N+1 qubits as follows:"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                137,
                395,
                855,
                514
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "equation_interline",
            "content": {
                "math_content": "U _ {f} (| x \\rangle | y \\rangle) = | x \\rangle | y \\oplus f (x) \\rangle \\tag {5.1}",
                "math_type": "latex",
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/7341366a0a1359002ddfeb2fb17e1de107ea7dd391619c4f46517bbe1c956d51.jpg"
                }
            },
            "bbox": [
                386,
                528,
                853,
                546
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "where <sub>\u0000</sub> denotes addition modulo 2. If the input N+1 qubit state is a “democratic” superposition of all the states of the computational basis, tensored with <sub>|</sub>0<sub>i</sub> , we find"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                137,
                557,
                855,
                605
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "equation_interline",
            "content": {
                "math_content": "U _ {f} (\\frac {1}{\\sqrt {2 ^ {N}}} \\sum_ {x} | x \\rangle | 0 \\rangle) = \\frac {1}{\\sqrt {2 ^ {N}}} \\sum_ {x} | x \\rangle | f (x) \\rangle \\tag {5.2}",
                "math_type": "latex",
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/eb7d4b719964c30653752b38c98dce35f77dc6926bcb92fea5ff7def59578019.jpg"
                }
            },
            "bbox": [
                324,
                605,
                853,
                642
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "We see that applying "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "U _ { f }"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "only once has produced a state containing all the values of the function "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "f ,"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "an operation that classically would require "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "2 ^ { N }"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "evaluations of the function "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "f ,"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "one for each value of the variable x. But extracting this information from the output state is not so easy. Measuring the N+1 qubit output state in the computational basis yields a particular value for x, giving the corresponding value for "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "f ( x )"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ", and destroys all the rest of the information (all the other "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "x , f ( x )"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "values). We will see in next Section how interference may be used to recover more information."
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                137,
                647,
                855,
                782
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "The superposed state "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "\\textstyle { \\frac { 1 } { \\sqrt { N } } } \\sum _ { x } \\left| x \\right."
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "can be easily obtained by using N Hadamard gates on N qubits in the state <sub>|</sub>0<sub>i</sub>:"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                137,
                783,
                855,
                821
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "equation_interline",
            "content": {
                "math_content": "(H \\otimes H \\otimes \\dots \\otimes H) | 0 \\rangle | 0 \\rangle \\dots | 0 \\rangle = \\frac {1}{\\sqrt {2 ^ {N}}} (| 0 \\rangle + | 1 \\rangle) (| 0 \\rangle + | 1 \\rangle) \\dots (| 0 \\rangle + | 1 \\rangle) = \\frac {1}{\\sqrt {2 ^ {N}}} \\sum_ {x} | x \\rangle \\tag {5.3}",
                "math_type": "latex",
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/52687d481380ccfee1e49b1eaba663ee896555d939130a04ffab2bcbf128d8c7.jpg"
                }
            },
            "bbox": [
                142,
                832,
                853,
                887
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "page_number",
            "content": {
                "page_number_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "21"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                487,
                906,
                507,
                919
            ]
        }
    ],
    [
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "The combined action of the Hadamard gates and the "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "U _ { f }"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "operator is represented by the following circuit:"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                137,
                125,
                857,
                160
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": {
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/15683c7ec635490b6eba0fcbcd9d935b2c7e6b3eaea1c69c99aa812497a63785.jpg"
                },
                "content": "```mermaid\ngraph LR\n  A[\"|0⟩\"] --> B[\"H\"]\n  C[\"|0⟩\"] --> D[\"H\"]\n  E[\"|0⟩\"] --> F[\"H\"]\n  G[\"|0⟩\"] --> H[\"H\"]\n  B --> I[\"Uf\"]\n  D --> I\n  F --> I\n  H --> I\n  I --> J[\"\"]\n  J --> K[\"1/√2^N ∑_x |x⟩|f(x)⟩\"]\n```",
                "image_caption": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Fig. 5.1 Parallel evaluation of a Boolean function f"
                    }
                ],
                "image_footnote": []
            },
            "sub_type": "flowchart",
            "bbox": [
                231,
                166,
                584,
                299
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "list",
            "content": {
                "list_type": "text_list",
                "list_items": [
                    {
                        "item_type": "text",
                        "item_content": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "content": "<sub>•</sub> Exercise: prove that "
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "equation_inline",
                                "content": "U _ { f }"
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "content": "is unitary."
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "item_type": "text",
                        "item_content": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "content": "<sub>•</sub> Exercise: find the circuit that implements "
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "equation_inline",
                                "content": "U _ { f }"
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "content": "when "
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "equation_inline",
                                "content": "N = 1"
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "content": "."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                139,
                342,
                680,
                391
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "5.2 Deutsch algorithm"
                    }
                ],
                "level": 2
            },
            "bbox": [
                139,
                412,
                428,
                432
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "This algorithm allows to find whether a function "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "f"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "is constant or nonconstant, by combining parallelism and interference. Consider the circuit:"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                137,
                440,
                858,
                473
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": {
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/f4a5f0c3d5119a5c8b59190db2320582299b1be56fdc8f2fd3f9f4976d2884c3.jpg"
                },
                "content": "```mermaid\ngraph LR\n  A[\"|0⟩\"] --> B[\"H\"]\n  C[\"|1⟩\"] --> D[\"H\"]\n  B --> E[\"Uf\"]\n  D --> E\n  E --> F[\"H\"]\n  F --> G[\"Output\"]\n```",
                "image_caption": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Fig. 5.2 Circuit for Deutsch’s algorithm "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "f"
                    }
                ],
                "image_footnote": []
            },
            "sub_type": "flowchart",
            "bbox": [
                193,
                498,
                563,
                568
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "where "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "U _ { f }"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "is defined in (5.1). Following the evolution of the initial 2-qubit state "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "| 0 \\rangle | 1 \\rangle"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "through the unitary gates yields as final state:"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                137,
                617,
                858,
                654
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "equation_interline",
            "content": {
                "math_content": "\\frac {| 0 \\rangle | f (0) \\rangle - | 0 \\rangle | 1 \\oplus f (0) \\rangle}{\\sqrt {2}} = \\pm | 0 \\rangle \\frac {| 0 \\rangle - | 1 \\rangle}{\\sqrt {2}} \\quad \\text {if} f (0) = f (1) \\tag {5.4}",
                "math_type": "latex",
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/512e2cc67f6d6e8de5a328f329d04aaabefe5805bdbc003c82760df6b40f6cf2.jpg"
                }
            },
            "bbox": [
                231,
                663,
                853,
                701
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "equation_interline",
            "content": {
                "math_content": "\\frac {| 1 \\rangle | f (0) \\rangle - | 1 \\rangle | f (1) \\rangle}{\\sqrt {2}} \\quad = \\pm | 1 \\rangle \\frac {| 0 \\rangle - | 1 \\rangle}{\\sqrt {2}} \\quad \\text {if} f (0) \\neq f (1) \\tag {5.5}",
                "math_type": "latex",
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/85129188693895328ca6e2b455b61924ac5e06a6e18281c213e6e21d510338c7.jpg"
                }
            },
            "bbox": [
                233,
                712,
                853,
                751
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "or in a single formula:"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                137,
                755,
                334,
                771
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "equation_interline",
            "content": {
                "math_content": "\\pm | f (0) \\oplus f (1) \\rangle \\frac {| 0 \\rangle - | 1 \\rangle}{\\sqrt {2}} \\tag {5.6}",
                "math_type": "latex",
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/e892406d41b6d630b4a0a0b560757c73e07cb18136151b31d099423cc461c96d.jpg"
                }
            },
            "bbox": [
                394,
                769,
                853,
                806
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Thus by measuring the first qubit we can determine whether the function f is constant (result 0) or nonconstant (result 1). Constancy of "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "f"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "is a global property, and classically two evaluations of "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "f"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "would be necessary to establish it, while a single application of Deutsch’s quantum circuit is su\u0000cient."
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                137,
                811,
                858,
                878
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "page_number",
            "content": {
                "page_number_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
